<br>
&quot;You a well mannered young man.&quot;  ::He spoke to Hermes::<br>
<br>
::His eyes then left Hermes and drifted to his wife, his love, Persephone.  For a brief moment his stone face turned to that of a joyous smile.  In his mind, she was the only color in his drab, grey world.:: <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#003366><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub11.ezboard.com/umeihao.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Meihao</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>registered user</span><br>  Posts: 9<br> <font color=#FFFF33>(6/29/01 7:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub11.ezboard.com/famazonsunitefrm23.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=63.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Trichromatic Flame</span><hr size=1> Holding onto his mother, Hermes realized the portence of this event.  He was being examined, measured, weighed, by each and every deity.  Was he a threat, could he be a threat, or could he be a possible ally?  These and many others were the unspoken questions apparent in everyone's mind.<br>
<br>
And so Hermes held onto Maia that much harder.  The strength and courage she had shown him, prevented him from turning around and running.  It would be so easy, to just disappear, Hermes thought, the world is so big, and filled with so many places to hide.  <br>
<br>
&quot;No, I must be strong&quot; whispered Hermes to himself.  <br>
<br>
He was starting to feel confident until the Erinyes blew in.  His knees were about to shake, when Maia mentally projected to him &quot;Be strong my son, be strong, for the both of us.&quot;  Looking up, Hermes nodded to his mother, and readied himself.<br>
<br>
It was like being in the presence of a living inferno.  How could beings encompass so much anger, even immortal beings, without combusting spontaneously?<br>
<br>
Alecto was the first to approach.  Borne upon the heat of the deadly Sahara desert, Alecto was outright dangerous.  Hermes tasted bitterness, the bitterness of very pungent medicine.  The kind that either cured if you were strong enough to last through its effects, and the kind that killed if you failed.  <br>
<br>
Hermes let out a small breath of relief when Alecto had tired of toying with him.  Until he saw Megaera.  <br>
<br>
Megaera was slick, the kind you try to scrub yourself off of, and no matter how hard you try, it still clings on.  Hermes realized there was a  difference between Megaera and Aphrodite.  Aphrodite is naughty, but playful.  But Megaera is the kind of naughtiness that can get you into very serious trouble.  In a sense, Megaera is like a drug, very sensuous and deadly.  One taste, and you become hooked.  You long for more, and will do anything for it.  Until nothing in the world matters.  Megaera is like that.  Touch her once, taste her once, and you're burnt for life.<br>
<br>
With terror, Hermes realizd that he still had one more sister to deal with with.  Tisiphone, probably the most deadly of all of the three sisters.  She approached Hermes directly, without even acknowledging Maia, and offered Hermes a present.  Hermes watched the innocent-enough toy, but realized the connotations to it.<br>
<br>
Tisiphone is very cunning.  Hermes realized that she was very similar to a deadly flame.  A flame so deceptively warm, and so very welcoming.  The kind a weary traveler dreams will be burning in the fireplace when he comes home.  But not knowing that the flame would suddenly erupt, so large would it become that the inferno would burn both home and occupant.  That was what Tisiphone was.  The deadly hunter, setting a trap to ensnare the unaware.  To Hermes, she tasted like blood, bitter and sweet.  The cloying sweetness that draws the prey ever closer to its death, and the bitterness of knowing that one is forever doomed.<br>
<br>
As Tisiphone showed Hermes the toy, Hermes pretended that he was enraptured by it.  But he secretly hoped his charade would not be discovered.  Hermes wanted desperately to remain unnoticed by the Erinyes.  Being burned once would be painful enough, but being burned thrice would surely be deadly.<br>
 <br>
