She was thankful for those who seemed to stand by here, yet she was still cautious.<br>
As Apollo took Hermes and became playful with him, she calmed down a bit of her motherly protective instincts. Maia could tell that Apollo was going to be an important brother to her son.   And that he already cared much for him.  This brought her a bit of peace.  <br>
Her eyes turned to Alecto and she scowled in her low, yet sultry voice, &quot;I do not fear Hera.  This is not the first time she has sought my death.  It is just the first time I bore her &quot;husband&quot; a son.&quot;  Narrowed eyes glared at the Erinyes.  She knew the Titan's power.  She herself was the daughter of Atlas.  Even if Maia's own powers were weak, she had a strong heart and will. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#003366><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub11.ezboard.com/uixlordhadesxi.showPublicProfile?language=EN>IX Lord Hades XI</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>registered user</span><br>  Posts: 73<br> <font color=#FFFF33>(6/30/01 1:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub11.ezboard.com/famazonsunitefrm23.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=63.topic&index=30>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How Rude!</span><hr size=1> ::Hades listened to Persephone proverbially bite Artemis's head off and merely smirked.  Yet another reason he was attracted to her, when she got upset she could be extremely feisty, he throught to himself.  He continued to stand there in observance of all:: <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#336699><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub11.ezboard.com/umeihao.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Meihao</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>registered user</span><br>  Posts: 10<br> <font color=#FFFF33>(6/30/01 3:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub11.ezboard.com/famazonsunitefrm23.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=63.topic&index=31>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Symbolic Gesture</span><hr size=1> Hermes was about to reply to his uncle, but when he looked into his uncle's eyes, he realized his uncle wouldn't even the know the world had exploded.  His uncle was completely mesmerized by his enchanting wife.<br>
<br>
Smiling a secretive smile, Hermes turned around.  He knew through instinct that someone very special was approaching.  In a blaze of golden fire, Athena emerged.  It was as if molten gold had taken form, for she was decked out in glorious auric splendor.<br>
<br>
Hermes became intrigued by the gogon's head emblazed upon Athena's breastplate.  It seemed the gorgon was still alive, still attempting to petrify any who dared to gaze in her direction.<br>
<br>
Hermes laughed to himself.  His cousin had wrested the city of Athens from their uncle Poseidon through a simple olive tree.  To Hermes, that's what Athena tasted like. It wasn't that Athena tasted like an olive tree, it was that Athena tasted of victory.  Whether victory was obtained through tremendous hardship, or through simple sharp wit, victory is still an ambrosia.  And to Hermes, that's what Athena was.  A woman of incredible fortitude and morals, who understands that the reward comes not only from the accomplishment of the goal, but also through the struggle as well.   <br>
<br>
Before Hermes could say anything to Athena, he was suddenly swept up onto the powerful arms of his brother.  Giggling, Hermes sat upon Apollo's broad shoulder, while playfully twirling Apollo's golden hair.  He realized what a great couple Athena and Apollo would be, if they were not so closely related.  He of the golden hair and she of the golden flame.  <br>
<br>
Feeling as if he was sitting on top of the world, Hermes waved playfully at his mother and to his other cousins.<br>
Then suddenly, as if a sudden cloud had suddenly eclipsed the sun, in swept another of his cousins, Artemis.<br>
<br>
Hermes could tell from the sudden bunching of Apollo's muscles, that he did not get along very well with his sister.  And judging from the scowl upon Athena's face, she disapproved of Artemis as well.<br>
<br>
Athena doesn't like the way Artemis approached her goals.  Artemis will gain, through any means, obtain her goals, whether they be noble or foul.  Being the goddess of the moon, and therefore of the dark, Artemis was not above using trickery and deceit.  This Athena abhors, for it made a mockery of her noble morals.<br>
<br>
As Hermes sat upon Apollo's shoulder, he was shocked at the kind of disrespect Artemis was showing to his mother.  Somehow Apollo must have sensed the unhappiness for he tightened his hold upon Hermes, and patted Hermes on his knees.<br>
<br>
Apollo and Artemis, the immortal twins, were like the two sides of the same coin.  One was shiny, bright and new, whereas the other was the dark, and old.  Therefore whenever there was a coin toss, the victor would offer thanks to the sun, whereas the loser would often curse his luck moon.<br>
<br>
Artemis tasted like nightshade, a poison that grows through the  glory of moonlight.  Tasteless and odorless, it made a great tool to remove ones enemies and even friends without detection.  It is often said that Artemis coated her arrows with nightshade.<br>
<br>
Hermes asked Apollo if he could set him down.  Once back on the ground, Hermes went to his mother.  Seeing the sorrow in her eyes, Hermes nodded to Athena, thanking her for the idea.  <br>
<br>
With a grand gesture, Hermes created an ivory throne, made from the tusks of the long-gone wooly mammoths.  With patterns created of jade, gold, and platinum, it showed the glories of Maia and of her glorious lineage.  Carved upon the throne are the names her devoted worshippers used to thank her for her blessings.  Stretched over the seat were cushions made of the finest Polynesian silk, stuffed with wool, sheared from the finest Malaysian mountain rams.<br>
<br>
Bowing to his mother, Hermes presented his humble gift.  After all, this is his mother, to him, the most prized and valuable being in all his life.  She deserved at least a throne worthy of her stature.<br>
<br>
Seeing the smile upon his mother's face, only made Hermes heart jump with pride.  Mentally projecting to Athena and Apollo his many thanks.  Hermes eagerly climbed onto his mother's lap.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#003366><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub11.ezboard.com/umeihao.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Meihao</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>registered user</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#FFFF33>(6/30/01 6:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub11.ezboard.com/famazonsunitefrm23.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=63.topic&index=32>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Persephone</span><hr size=1> As Hermes sat upon his mother's lap, he realized how upset Persephone was becoming.  All because of him, it seemed.  Hermes felt very lucky to have such wonderful people in his lives.  Getting off his mother's lap, Hermes went over to Persephone.<br>
<br>
Floating slowly up, Hermes gently placed a kiss upon his cousin's flawless skin.  This caused Persephone to focus on Hermes instead.<br>
<br>
&quot;Thank you cousin,&quot; whispered Hermes to Persephone.  As he gently floated around her.  Then Hermes took her hand and led her over to his mother.<br>
<br>
Maia stood up and gave Persephone a hug that spoke volumes.  And together, they sat upon the throne, clasping each other's hands.<br>
